about.label: Example loader
about.description: Use this box to load example simulations from the VEDA manual

about.label: Initial gap (nm)
about.description: The initial tip-sample gap.

about.label: Final gap separation (nm)
about.description: The final tip-sample gap.

about.label: Number of points plotted
about.description: The number of data points plotted/saved.

about.label: Velocity options (for non-conservative tip-sample interaction models)
about.description: Choose the velocity profile used to calculate non-conservative forces exterted by the tip on the sample.

about.label: None / quasi-static
about.description: velocity = zero will be assumed.

about.label: Half sine Wave
about.description: sine wave

about.label: Triangle Wave
about.description: Linear ramp.

about.label: Rounded Triangle Wave
about.description: Linear ramp. Moving average filter used to round off the bottom to avoid a discontinuity in velocity.

about.label: Duration (s)
about.description: Total simulation duration

about.label: Moving average filter length (%)
about.description: The length of the moving average filter used to round off the triangle. Larger number gives a wider region of rounding

about.label: Tip-sample interaction model
about.description: Choose a model to predict the forces exterted by the tip on the sample.

about.label: Linear contact
about.description: Interaction forces are predicted according to a (piece-wise) linear contact model for an overall stiffness, kts, of the sample.

about.label: Linear attractive/repulsive
about.description: Interaction forces are predicted according to a (piece-wise) linear contact model for an overall stiffness, kts_r, of the sample, and an attractive-force gradient, kts_a.

about.label: Hertz contact
about.description: Hertz contact model with no attractive forces.

about.label: DMT contact
about.description: Derjaguin-Muller-Toporov (DMT) contact model including van der Waals attractive forces.

about.label: DMT + DLVO interactions (liquids)
about.description: Derjaguin-Muller-Toporov + Derjaguin-Landau-Verwey-Overbeek (electrical double layer) interaction forces.

about.label: JKR
about.description: Johnson-Kendall-Roberts interaction forces.

about.label: Chadwick
about.description: Chadwick interaction model for a very thin membrane loosely bound to a stiff substrate.

about.label: Hertz contact with bottom effect correction for thin samples
about.description: Interaction model for a moderately thin sample loosely bound to a stiff substrate. Dimitriadis et al for spherical tip shape. Gavara and Chadwick for conical

about.label: Van der Waals + Morse Potential
about.description: Morse potential is used in non-contact FM-AFM to model bonding interation. Should NOT be used for AM-AFM in tapping mode, or in any repulsive regime.

about.label: Van der Waals + Lennard Jones Potential
about.description: Lennard Jones potential is used in non-contact FM-AFM to model attractive regime. Should NOT be used for AM-AFM in tapping mode, or in any repulsive regime.

about.label: Electrostatic Forces (noncontact), Gil et al. + van der Waals
Magnetic dipole-dipole (sphere-sphere, Rasa et al)
about.description: This is the sphere-sphere model equation 6 from M. Rasa, B.W.M. Kuipers, P. Philipse, Journal of Colloid and Interface Science 2002, 250, 303-15.

about.label: Attard's model (Viscoelastic contact with attractive forces)
about.description: Use the method of Attard to compute viscoelastic contact with adhesion.

about.label: Tip shape
about.description: For Hertz and DMT contact models, either a paraboloid or cone tip can be selected. For JKR and other models, only a paraboloid is implemented

about.label: Classical sphere (i.e. paraboloid), default
about.description: This is a paraboloid, which is a reasonable approximation to a sphere when the sphere radius is much larger than the area of contact. If you are not sure pick this one.

about.label: Cone
about.description: Circular cone. Generally this is only valid for high cone angles. For small cones angles the material will plastically deform

about.label: Cone half-angle (deg)
about.description: Half-angle of the conical tip.

van der Waals Adhesion force (nN)
about.description: The adhesion force is the attractive force applied on the cantilever tip by the sample by van der Waals forces just before contact, neglecting any capillary forces. This force could be obtained from an F-z curve (in dry nitrogen or another environment where capillary forces are negligible). Capillary force contributions to adhesion are described seperately below

about.label: Non-conservative solvation forces (viscous)
about.description: This models the non-conservative component of solvation forces as a viscosity that decays exponentially away from the surface. Note: Jeffery proposed that damping was proportional to stiffness, which includes oscillatory forces, but we model only a monotonic damping coefficient.
